e tastier and grown in more ecologically sustainable ways, this approach can also reinforce class and race inequalities and neglect other possible explanations for the rise in obesity, including environmental toxins. Arguing that ours is a political economy of bulimia—one that promotes consumption while also insisting upon thinness—Guthman offers a complex analysis of our entire economic system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aObesityxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  abody weight ideals.  abulimia.  acapitalism.  acauses of obesity.  aclass differences.  aconsumption.  adiet ethics.  aeconomic system.  aenvironmental toxins.  afarm fresh.  afat.  afood and culture.  afood justice.  afood system.  ahealth and diet.  ahealth care system.  alocal food.  anonfiction.  aobesity in america.  aobesity prevention.  aobesity.  aorganic food.  apolitics of food.  aprocessed foods.  aracial inequality.  asocial inequality.  asociologists.  asociology.  asustainable food.  aus economics.  aweight loss.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026624740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094975140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520949751423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520949751/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY